# DishCheck — Cursor Standing Instructions
# Read before every prompt. These rules are non-negotiable.

## What this project is
DishCheck is a dish-level review web app. Users search for a specific dish
at a specific restaurant and read or write reviews with photo + sub-ratings
(taste, portion, value) + tags. Built with Next.js 14 App Router, Firebase,
Tailwind CSS, Zustand, and TanStack Query. Deployed on Vercel.

## Architecture rules
- ALL Firebase SDK calls go through lib/firebase/ functions only.
  Never import Firebase SDK directly inside components or pages.
- ALL TypeScript types come from lib/types/index.ts.
  Never define types inline. Never use `any`.
- UI primitives live in components/ui/ only.
  Feature components live in components/features/ only.
  Never mix them.
- Custom hooks live in lib/hooks/. Hooks call lib/firebase/ functions.
  Hooks never call Firebase SDK directly.
- Constants (tags, badges, levels) come from lib/constants/index.ts.
  Never hardcode these values inline.

## shadcn UI rules (non-negotiable)
- ALL basic UI elements MUST use shadcn components from components/ui/.
  Never use raw `<button>`, `<input>`, `<select>`, or `<label>` in pages
  or feature components. Use `<Button>`, `<Input>`, `<Select>`, `<Label>`.
- Available shadcn primitives: Button, Input, Badge, Label, Select,
  Sheet, DropdownMenu. If a primitive doesn't exist, add it via
  `npx shadcn add <component>` before using it.
- For composition (e.g. Button as Link), use the `render` prop:
  `<Button render={<Link href="..." />}>`. Never use `asChild`.
- Tailwind overrides via `className` are fine for one-off tweaks, but
  the base component MUST come from shadcn. Never recreate Button/Input
  from scratch with raw elements + Tailwind.

## Code style
- TypeScript strict mode. No `any`. No `ts-ignore`. No implicit returns.
- Functional components only. No class components.
- Named exports for components. Default exports for Next.js pages only.
- Every async component must handle loading state and error state.
- No inline styles. Tailwind classes only.
- No CSS modules. No styled-components.
- Prefer early returns over nested conditionals.

## Firebase rules
- Collection names: always import from lib/firebase/config.ts COLLECTIONS object.
  Never hardcode collection name strings.
- Always use Firestore Timestamp, never JS Date.
- Always wrap Firebase calls in try/catch. Return null or [] on error.
  Never let Firebase errors propagate silently.
- Wishlist subcollection path: users/{userId}/wishlist/{dishId}.

## Feature gates
- Premium features (advanced filters, dish comparison):
  Check user.isPremium === true before rendering. Show <UpgradePrompt /> if false.
- Admin features: check user.isAdmin === true.
  Redirect to "/" if false. Never render admin UI for non-admins.

## What NOT to do
- Do not add features not in the sprint scope.
- Do not change the data model without explicit instruction.
- Do not write Firestore security rules (human writes these).
- Do not use localStorage for anything auth-related.
- Do not install new packages without asking first.
- Do not refactor and add features in the same response.
